\section{Introduction}

Creating web applications is hard. Creating high quality web applications which are delivered on time and on budget is even more difficult. Developers must not only master web development technologies, but web development methodologies as well. Previous research has shown that X\% of the cost of a typical web application is incurred during the maintenance phase of web project. \todo{update these values and cite} This means that developers need to pay special attention to ensuring that their applications are created in a maintainable fashion. Developers also need to balance the concepts of uptime, security, worldwide availability and access through numerous devices by end customers.

Web Engineering is defined as the systematic, disciplined and quantifiable approach to development, operation and maintenance of web-based systems and applications ~\cite{Schummer:2005:TDS:1149293.1149369,Mendes:2003:ACF:858403.858417,Reif:2005:WWE:1060745.1060849}. While similar to software engineering, the concept of web engineering differs in several key areas~\cite{Ginige:2002:WEM:568760.568885}. Web Engineering places a higher emphasis on growth and change, compressed schedules, performance criticality and small teams working on very short schedules~\cite{Deshpande:2002:WE:2011098.2011101}. Unfortunately, while many institutions offer classes in programming web applications, or even Software Engineering, very few offer courses in Web Engineering~\cite{tufts_webengineering,csun_webengineering}.
\dan{Did I describe web engineering enough?}

At the Department of Software Engineering at \ifisnopii the Rochester Institute of Technology (RIT)\else xxxxxx\fi, we created a Web Engineering course to help meet the demands that students would face upon graduation when creating web applications. The purpose of this course is to instruct students in using proper Web Engineering principles when creating web applications. We developed a course project component where teams are comprised of 3-5 students in a term long project and create a web application in multiple iterations using a variety of contemporary technologies and resources.

The goal of the project is to reinforce course concepts and allow students to gain experience creating web applications in a team environment using current technologies while applying Web Engineering concepts. Student teams are expected to fulfill all steps of the software development lifecycle including the successful creation of all necessary requirement, design, test, and deployment documents, along with the development of the project using the proper principles of Web Engineering. We have found that this project is invaluable at reinforcing concepts discussed in the classroom, while providing an enjoyable, real world experience for the students.

The rest of the paper is organized as follows: Section~\ref{sec: aboutcourse} describes the course including weekly topics, and provides an outline of weekly project deliverables. Section~\ref{sec: aboutproject} provides an overview of the project detailing requirements, deliverables and evaluation methods. Section~\ref{sec: studentfeedback} provides some student feedback regarding the project, while Section~\ref{sec: relatedwork} presents some related works. Section~\ref{sec: futurework} describes some future work and Section~\ref{sec: summary} concludes the paper with a summary.
