\section{About the project}
\label{sec: aboutproject}

The project lasted the entire term of the course (which in our case is 15 weeks), and had student teams of 3-5 students create several deliverables throughout the term. Team size is targeted to 4-6 students, as this is often the size of groups in industry and has been found to be conducive to student learning in previous research~\cite{Guo:2009:GPS:1516546.1516579,Petkovic:2006:TPS:1140124.1140202}.

\subsection{Project Requirements}
% Instructor should feel free to tweak these as they see fit

The main premise of the project was for each group to create a web portal using both custom built and already existing components through web service and Application Programming Interface (API) calls. A group project was an important aspect of the course since they have been found to be extremely beneficial to student learning~\cite{Schummer:2005:TDS:1149293.1149369,Guo:2009:GPS:1516546.1516579,Coppit:2005:LTP:1047124.1047400}. We required teams to develop their producing using the Microsoft .Net framework, although this project is adaptable for use in a large number of contemporary web technologies.

The first of several factors for selecting this project is that it represented a real world product, using real world technologies. This is important since the goal of the project was to emulate what the students would see in their careers after college. Additionally realistic development goals help to further challenge and encourage students~\cite{Schummer:2005:TDS:1149293.1149369,Marmorstein:2011:OSC:1999747.1999823,Tadayon:2004:SEB:1050231.1050248,VanderDuim:2007:GPE:1248820.1248900,Hayes:2002:ESE:872751.873465}. Another reason for selecting an activity like this was to foster student interest in the project. Developing a solution using APIs from well-known and respected companies greatly excited the students. This enthusiasm helped them remain focused and drive their desire to learn and overall ingenuity.

The instructor took on two distinct roles for the project: teacher and customer. The way the customer reacts to student questions significantly differs depending on what role the instructor is currently playing. While representing the role of teacher, the instructor may give project advice and answer technical questions wherever possible. As the customer, they attempted to mimic a client in the real world and students were encouraged to clarify requirements with them. So students may understand which role the instructor is playing, students are encouraged to ask whenever they are unsure and begin their statements with ``As the customer'' or ``As the teacher.''

The goal of the project is to create a personalized web portal that would be customized for each user. We chose to require that the user login with their Facebook account. We selected these criteria not only because the Facebook API was readily available, but because we felt that incorporating Facebook here would help to encourage student interest in the project. Students of the millennial generation have been found to be more engaged with programming projects that have a social relevance, which made a project such as this even more applicable~. Once the user logged into the application, they are exposed to several pieces of personal, customizable information. One of the most significant is an area on the main page which is very similar to the wall in the traditional Facebook application. For this section, students were asked to again tie into the Facebook API to retrieve the necessary data. They were required to modify the appearance of these items and utilize aspects of usability covered in the course. Various other Facebook APIs such as photo albums, chatting with friends and status updates were used in similar ways.

\dan{Show a mockup or wireframe of what the project should look like?}


Several other aspects of the project required the students to write custom software to interact with extra data services or feeds. Students were asked to incorporate a stock viewing web page into their project. The user would initially enter in a stock that they fictitiously purchased along with the purchase price and number of shares. This information would be stored in a student created MS-SQL database. For all of these simulated purchased stocks, information would be retrieved from a third party web service and the page would be expected to display the current stock price, the day's high and low price, along with the amount of money the investment has thus far made or lost for the buyer. A chart is also displayed for the stock which is retrieved using an external feed of the group's choice. Other aspects of the application include a weather based component and a chat feature based upon HTML5. The reason for this chat component is to both familiarize the students with HTML5 and to acquaint them with how to properly place and utilize such an interactive element.

Teams were also expected to write their code in a clean manner while using a version control system of their choosing. Since teams would be producing multiple releases, each team was provided a Windows Server virtual machine to deploy their project to, and were expected to produce and adhere to a robust deployment strategy. Although this is not a security course, this is still a paramount topic for software, especially web applications. Projects were required to use proper defensive coding practices to protect against SQL injection, and cross site scripting attacks. Based on the desires of the specific instructor, they may wish to place more emphasis on these topics though.


\subsection{Weekly Actions \& Deliverables}
In order to mimic the iterative nature that web applications are usually created in\todo{cite}, we required teams to submit multiple project releases. These submissions also served to reinforce the importance of maintainability and extensibility in web applications. While we encourage instructors to deviate from this plan as necessary, we will describe the deliverables and project releases below.\\

% State something about the deliverables also being shown in Table 1 ?

\textbf{1) Team Formation}\\
Teams were formed using an on-line survey where students indicated who they would like to work with, and rather not work with. Students also described their level of level of experience with web development and software engineering in order for the instructor to create more balanced. teams.

Each team consists of several roles including team coordinator, development coordinator and testing coordinator. Since the course was comprised of upper level students, they were given the opportunity to self-appoint these roles. We believe that this level of freedom will make the students feel less restricted. If the class was primarily made up of more novice students, the instructor may want to appoint team roles.
 \\

\textbf{3) Requirements Documents}\\
Students are provided with a requirements document template which they are will out based on their conversations with the customer/instructor. As with all documentation, teams are expected to keep these documents up to date for all releases throughout the term.

The grading on these initial document deliverables was not aimed at ensuring that the teams had a completely accurate document on their first attempt. The main goal was for the students to have followed the proper guidelines for producing these deliverables and that an adequate effort was at least given to create them as accurately as possible. During the second half of the class each team was given the opportunity to meet with the instructor to ask requirements and general project questions. In these interactions, the students were also able to negotiate expectations with the customer. They were encouraged to show prototypes, screenshots and anything else they desired to the customer. The goal was not to limit customer interaction, or punish inquisitions as long as they were reasonable. The aim was to encourage customer interaction and elicitation.\\

\textbf{5) Design Documents \& Test Plan}\\
As with the requirements document, teams are provided a template design document and are expected to use the requirements they've been provided and elicited from the customer as input for this design document. Some document components include UML state, sequence and class diagrams. Teams are also expected to create a test plan for their project. For our course offerings, teams were instructed to create acceptance tests in a simple excel document. However, instructors may choose to have teams use a more robust tool should they see fit. \\

\textbf{6) Beta Release}\\
The initial project release is intended to be a lightly scrutinized preview of R1. If time allows, Instructors are encouraged to allow teams to conduct a short 5 minute demo of their applications and progress and elicit feedback from their classmates. This activity has been very successful for us and students have enjoyed seeing the progress of their classmates and gaining this extra feedback before their first major project deliverable.\\

\textbf{7) Release 1}\\
Teams were asked to deliver a partially working version of their application, along with a presentation. Teams are expected to submit all updated project documentation including the requirements, design and test plan. As will all releases, students are required to complete an on-line, 360 survey about their teammates in order to identify problematic areas of the team and team members who are not contributing as much as they should to the project. Teams may be evaluated upon their presentation, updated documentation, and created software. Some key application features they should have completed are connections with the external APIs and deployment strategy and implementation. We did not evaluate usability or database setup for this initial release.

The Software Engineering Department at \ifisnopii RIT \else xxxxxx \fi places a large emphasis on public speaking, presentation and overall communication skills for their students. For the first release, each group was asked to give a 15 minute presentation about some of the major aspects and technologies used in their project. Other areas discussed were team roles and dynamics, a short demonstration of their application and their plan for the second release. The presentation was oriented as a progress report for the customer.

One interesting aspect we ask the students to denote is any missing features which they were not able to deliver for the initial release. These are any requirements that the group promised to deliver to the customer, but were unable to do so. In order to help persuade the students to divulge these undelivered items, they are told they will be penalized much less significantly for any items that they declared to have missed as compared to if the instructor/customer found them on their own. There are several benefits in having the students reveal these missed items. The first is that it forces the students to take ownership of their mistakes and be honest and open with their customers. This is something which we feel to be important once the students graduate to the real world. The second reason is that it helps the students to be open about self-identifying problems with their work and areas of improvement. \\


\textbf{8) R1 Post Mortem}\\
Each group is asked to work on a team self-reflection document. Components of this paper include identifying areas of the project that went well, along with portions of the project which can be improved and how. Students are encouraged to deeply think and elaborate on these areas of went well and what can be improved. Teams are encouraged to overly elaborate or discuss overly technical issues which they have encountered. Post mortems will be evaluated on their thoroughness, identification of strengths and weakness and plans to overcome these deficiencies. We have seen quality submissions be in the 3-5 single spaced page range, but individual instructors will want to alter this guideline as they see fit.\\


\textbf{11) R2}\\
Teams will submit their projects, updated documents and conduct a presentation in a similar fashion to their first release. In order to save class time, team presentations may be abbreviated to 5 minutes, or even excluded at the discretion of the instructor. Teams will be evaluated on how well they are updating their documentation, adhered to web engineering principles, and the quality of their application. Some expected additional features for R2 include better usability, use of a database backend, and implemented messaging component.\\



\textbf{12) R2 Post Mortem}\\
Similar submission at the R1 post mortem. \\



