\section{Future work}
\label{sec: futurework}

While the project has seen considerable success since its first inception three years ago, there is still work to be done and areas of improvement. Web technologies change at a tremendously fast rate, and keeping the course up to date is always a challenge. Instructors need to remember that while the technologies used in the course and project are important, this is a class whose primary focus is on instructing proper engineering principles and programming is of secondary importance.

Like with many team based projects, a problem we encountered was how to deal with students who do not contribute to the project. This is a dilemma which is not at all unique to this project and occurs in a wide variety of software engineering student projects~\cite{VanderDuim:2007:GPE:1248820.1248900}. One way which we dealt with this issue was to ask students to fill out a brief peer review survey after reach major project deliverable. The goal was to identify non-contributing students at either of these stages and address the identified situations as necessary.

Instructors can expect students entering the course with a diverse range of experiences and skillsets, making it difficult to balance between having the project topics be challenging enough for the more advanced students, but simple enough for the less advanced students to not be left behind. This problem may be mitigated through the use of course pre-requisites, but is a challenge that instructors will need to balance with each course offering.


\section{Summary}
\label{sec: summary}

Using proper Web Engineering principles to create web applications which are on time, on budget, and high quality is a paramount skill for students to  master. We have created a project component for our Web Engineering course in order to reinforce the class's concepts with the goal of resembling a real world project which the students will face after graduation as closely as possible.

In several course offerings, we have refined the project to better suite it to the learning objectives of the course and to keep it relevant with the fast paced nature of web technologies. We have also seen a significant amount of student interest and enthusiasm about the project, which as carried over to the course as well. Student returning from their first jobs as Web Engineers have also stated that the project prepared them well for their job and the experiences they would be facing. Due to the success we have witnessed, we encourage others to use this project in their Web Engineering courses as well.



